<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-01-08T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-01-08T18:00:00-05:00" n="883" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d883">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 EAC/1–945: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Winant</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-01-09T00:00:00+01:00">January 9,
                                    1945—midnight</date>.<lb/>[Received January 10—12:18
                                a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>312. Comea<note n="93" xml:id="d883fn93">Series designation for telegrams
                                from London dealing with affairs in the European Advisory
                                Commission. Ambassador John G. Winant was U.S. representative on the
                                Commission.</note> 147. My 313, January 9, midnight.<note n="94" xml:id="d883fn94">
                                <hi rend="italic">Infra.</hi>
                            </note> At today’s meeting of the European Advisory Commission,
                                Strang,<note n="95" xml:id="d883fn95">Sir William Strang, United
                                Kingdom representative on the European Advisory Commission.</note>
                            supported by the French, pressed for early consideration of the British
                            proposal for the establishment of a restitution commission (my 10368,
                            November 24, 10 p.m. Comea 131<note n="96" xml:id="d883fn96">Not
                                printed.</note>). In line with Department’s 10731 of December 27, 4
                                p.m.,<note n="97" xml:id="d883fn97">
                                <ref target="frus1944v01#pg_426">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1944, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 426</ref>.</note> I gave no
                            indication that we would be ready for early discussion of restitution
                            and reparation.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Winant</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>